<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-349-172  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 349 172.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  June 1989 v6 n6 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sizing up the impact of image processing. (image processing in thebanking industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wagner, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Image processing is an example of how institutions seeking toimplement new technologies must first carefully assess theresulting effects on business strategy.andP;  'Ad hoc' automation oftenproves to be ineffective in the long term because it results indecentralization and confusion.andP;  Effective analysis of the impactof new technology considers four factors: the bank's businessgoals and objectives; information systems goals and objectives;current telecommunications network architecture; and industrytrends.andP;  The efficiency of image processing supports the goal ofproviding personalized customer services at low cost, but the newtechnology should not be implemented without first noting itsimpact on the workflow environment.andP;  Image processing impinges oncurrent data processing applications and may require extensiveredesign.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BankingComputer Systems IntegrationImage ProcessingAutomationDigitizersBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>